This is a '''timeline of [[healthcare in South Africa]]''', focusing especially on modern science-based medicine healthcare. Major events such as policies and organizations are described.
==Big picture== {| class="sortable wikitable" ! Year/period !! Key developments |- |17th–18th centuries||Hospital care is provided by the [[Dutch East India Company]], colonial governments, and Christian missions. Traditional healers, European trained doctors, missionaries, and other health providers offer a mix of services.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges">{{cite web|title=The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges|url=http://depts.washington.edu/sphnet/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Coovadia.pdf|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref> |- |19th century||Medically trained doctors become mainstream. Indigenous and traditional healers are marginalized. Orthodox medicine becomes a professional practice with training of nurses and doctors. By mid-century, hospitals are present in most major centers. Epidemics of [[syphilis]], [[tuberculosis]], [[bubonic plague]], [[yellow fever]], [[typhus]], [[cholera]], soil parasites, and malnutrition hit South Africa.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" /> |- |1910–1948||The [[Union of South Africa]] is established. Health services are fragmented among the four provinces. Poor urban working and living conditions with diseases are caused by overcrowding, poor sanitation and diets, stress, and social disintegration follow consolidation of racial segregation. Syphilis, tuberculosis, malaria and venereal diseases continue to spread.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" /> |- |1948–1994||[[Apartheid]] years. Non-communicable diseases rise in white people and poverty-related diseases persist in black people. Tuberculosis rates and deaths are much higher in black and coloured populations than among whites. Health services in [[bantustan]]s are systematically underfunded.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" /> |- |1994–present||Post-apartheid democracy. Today, the public system serves the vast majority of the population, but it still remains underfunded and understaffed. The wealthiest 20% of the population use the private system and are far better served.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" /> Diseases of poverty, non-communicable diseases and HIV/AIDS comprise a huge burden for South Africa. |}
==Full timeline== {| class="sortable wikitable" ! Year/period !! Type of event !! Event !!Location |- |1807||Policy||The first health legislation is enacted. A Supreme Medical Committee is established to oversee all health matters.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1830||Policy||Ordinance 82 allows for regulation of all health practices in the [[Cape Colony]]. Other three colonies follow.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1855||Organization||[[Grey’s Hospital]] is established.<ref>{{cite web|title=GREY'S HOSPITAL|url=http://www.kznhealth.gov.za/greyshospital.htm|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Pietermaritzburg]], [[KwaZulu-Natal]] |- |1881||Organization||[[Frere Hospital]] is established.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frere|url=http://www.tophealthclinics.com/clinic/367481746681155/Frere+Hospital|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>||[[East London]], [[Eastern Cape]] |- |1883||Policy||Public Health Act makes notification and inoculation of [[smallpox]] compulsory in response to smallpox epidemic.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1890||Organization||[[Valkenberg Hospital]] is founded.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valkenberg|url=http://www.samj.org.za/index.php/samj/article/view/5449/4222|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>|| |- |1892||Organization||[[Weskoppies Psychiatric Hospital]] is founded. It is the first psychiatric institution established in the [[Zuid-Afrikaansche Republiek]].<ref name="HISTORY OF MEDICINE">{{cite web|title=HISTORY OF MEDICINE|url=http://archive.samj.org.za/1992%20VOL%2081%20Jan-Jun/Articles/02%20February/2.11%20HISTORY%20OF%20MEDICINE%20-%20WESKOPPIES%20HOSPITAL,%20FOUNDED%201892%20-%20THE%20EARLY%20YEARS.%20C.%20Plug%20and%20J.L.%20.pdf|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Pretoria]], [[Gauteng]] |- |1897||Policy||Public Health Amendment Act is launched. It separates curative and preventive care.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1919||Organization||Health Act establishes the first Unionwide Public Health department in South Africa.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1933||Organization||[[Umlamli Hospital]] is established.<ref>{{cite web|title=Umlami|url=https://www.grid.ac/institutes/grid.461175.0|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>||[[Sterkspruit]], [[Eastern Cape]] |- |1938||Organization||[[Groote Schuur Hospital]] is founded. It is the chief academic hospital of the [[University of Cape Town]]'s medical school.<ref>{{cite web|title=Groote Schuur Hospital: Overview|url=https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/163|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Cape Town]] |- |1940||Report||There's an overall ratio of one doctor per 3600 population. There's one doctor for every 308 white people in Cape Town compared with one doctor for 22,000 to 30,000 people in the reserves.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1942||Organization||[[Chris Hani Baragwanath Hospital]] is founded. It is the largest hospital in the southern hemisphere and the third largest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Chris Hani Baragwanath Hospital|url=https://www.chrishanibaragwanathhospital.co.za/|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Johannesburg]] |- |1942–1944|| ||The National Health Service Commission (also called Gluckman Commission) is carried out. It advocates for a unitary national health service in South Africa.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1951||Organization||Segregated black medical faculty is created at the University of Natal (UNB).<ref name="Black Doctors and Discrimination under South Africa’s Apartheid Regime">{{cite journal|title=Black Doctors and Discrimination under South Africa's Apartheid Regime|doi=10.1017/mdh.2012.106|pmc=3867842 | pmid=24070349|volume=57|issue=2|year=2013|journal=Med Hist|pages=269–90 | last1 = Digby | first1 = A}}</ref>||[[KwaZulu-Natal]] |- |1955||Organization||[[Fort Grey TB Hospital]] is founded.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fort Grey TB Hospital|url=http://www.tophealthclinics.com/clinic/182561491886108/Fort+Grey+TB+Hospital|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>||[[East London, Eastern Cape]] |- |1959||Organization||[[Madwaleni Hospital]] is founded.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madwaleni Hospital|url=https://www.travelground.com/attractions/madwaleni-hospital|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Elliotdale]], [[Eastern Cape]] |- |1966||Organization||[[Jose Pearson TB Hospital]] is founded.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jose Pearson TB Hospital|url=http://www.findyourdoctor.net/2013/08/jose-pearson-tb-hospital-port-elizabeth.html|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>||[[Port Elizabeth]], [[Eastern Cape]] |- |1967||Achievement||South African cardiac surgeon [[Christiaan Barnard]] performs the world's first human heart transplant operation at [[Groote Schuur Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr Chris Barnard performs the world’s first human heart transplant|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/dated-event/dr-chris-barnard-performs-worlds-first-human-heart-transplant|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Cape Town]] |- |1972||Organization||[[Kalafong Hospital]] is founded. The [[University of Pretoria]] uses the hospital as a training institution for the Faculty of Health Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kalafong Hospital|url=http://www.up.ac.za/en/paediatrics-and-child-health/article/18881/kalafong-hospital|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |1976||Organization||[[Tygerberg Hospital]] is founded. It is the second largest hospital in South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tygerberg Hospital: Overview|url=https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/153|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Bellville, Western Cape]] |- |1977||Organization||Second training site for black medical students is created at the [[Sefako Makgatho Health Sciences University|Medical University of South Africa]] (MEDUNSA).<ref name="Black Doctors and Discrimination under South Africa’s Apartheid Regime" />||[[Pretoria]], [[Gauteng]] |- |1977||Policy||Health Act is passed, perpetuating the fragmentation with curative services being a provincial responsibility and prevention a local government responsibility.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1983||Policy||Tricameral Parliament further fragments health services with white, [[coloured]], and Indian ''own affairs'' departments.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1994||Policy||First democratic elections in South Africa are held. The country's race-based health system begins dismantling. A policy on universal access to primary healthcare is introduced.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa">{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaclub.co.za/democracy/34-democracy/developmentbg/102-healthcare|title=Healthcare in South Africa|last=|first=|date=|website=Media Club South Africa|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>|| |- |1996||Policy||Choice on Termination of Pregnancy Act is passed. This legislation legalizes abortion and allows for safe access to it in both public and private health facilities.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |1996||Policy||Free care for children younger than 6 years and pregnant women, and free primary health care for all South Africans is instituted.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |1998||Program||A National Telemedicine Project Strategy is adopted by the South African Department of Health. The system facilitates frequent contact between doctors in underdeveloped and developed areas.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |1998||Policy||Medical Schemes Act is passed. This legislation regulates the medical schemes industry to prevent it from discriminating against "high risk" individuals like the aged and sick.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |1999||Policy||Tobacco Products Control Amendment Act is passed. This legislation limits smoking in public places and makes the public aware of the health risks of tobacco by placing restrictions on tobacco advertisements.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2000||Policy||Pharmacy Amendment Act is passed. This legislation allows non-pharmacists to own pharmacies, with the aim of improving access to medicines.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2001||Policy||Free Basic Water Strategy defines water as a social and developmental good and basic human right.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |2002||Policy||Mental Healthcare Act is passed. This legislation introduces a process to develop and redesign mental health services so as to grant basic rights to people with mental illnesses.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2003||Program||The South African government launches the Hospital Revitalisation Programme, with a total budget of [[South African rand|R]] 1.9 billion, in an attempt to improve the public health system. Under the program, hospital infrastructure, procurement of the necessary equipment and management skills are improved.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2003||Organization||The National Reference Centre for African Traditional Medicines is launched to research African herbs and to evaluate their medicinal value.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2004||Program||The South African government launches the Community Health Worker Programme to develop community-based generalist health workers. Their training combines competencies in health promotion, disease prevention, primary healthcare and health-resource networking, as well as coordination. 40,000 such workers are estimated to be in South Africa.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2004||Policy||National Health Act is passed. Under this legislation, both the district health system and primary health care are defined as provincial responsibilities.<ref name="The health and health system of South Africa: historical roots of current public health challenges" />|| |- |2005||Policy||Nursing Act is passed. This legislation provides for the introduction of mandatory community service for nurses.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2006||Program||The National Human Resource Plan is launched by the South African Department of Health in an attempt to make up for the skills shortfall and to compensate for the loss of experienced health professionals from rural to urban areas, from the public to private sector, and from South Africa mainly to developed countries.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2006||Study||The Medicines Research Council (MRC) initiates toxicology studies to further study selected indigenous plants.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2006||Program||The Accelerated Prevention of HIV/Aids Initiative is launched as part of an extensive initiative regarding prevention by the member states of the Africa region of the [[WHO]]. More than 1 060 health professionals are recruited to support the program. Some 7 600 health professionals are trained in the management, care and treatment of [[HIV/AIDS]]. 213 000 patients initiate on antiretroviral treatment by the end of September 2006, and an estimated additional 90,000 to 100,000 patients initiate in the private and nongovernmental sector.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2007||Program||The South African government enters into an agreement to recruit 2,000 [[Tunisia]]n doctors to combat long standing shortage of doctors in rural areas. The Department of Health also employs 450 doctors from [[Cuba]] and [[Iran]].<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2007||Program||A new cadre of health professionals called clinical associates is introduced to lighten the workload at health facilities. Graduates are expected to work under the supervision of medical officers in district hospitals and primary healthcare level.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2007||Campaign||The South African Department of Health launches a nationwide Polio and Measles Immunisation Campaign. It is aimed at boosting the immunization coverage in the country.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2010||Report||150,509 qualified health practitioners in both public and private sectors are registered with the Health Professions Council of South Africa. This includes 30,006 doctors and 5,185 dentists.<ref name="Healthcare in South Africa" />|| |- |2016||Report||Life expectancy in [[South Africa]] is estimated at 49.99 years, being ranked 228th out of 228 political subdivisions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Life Expectancy|url=http://www.geoba.se/population.php?pc=world&type=015&year=2016&st=rank&asde=d&page=1|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref> South Africa is reported to have the lowest life expectancy in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Africa has the lowest life expectancy in the world|url=http://businesstech.co.za/news/general/118214/south-africa-has-the-lowest-life-expectancy-in-the-world/|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>|| |}
